segments.text: The following is an interview by Elmer Sparks with Celia Black, former slave of Tyler Texas.
This being October the 11th, 1974, many years have passed since Mrs. Black first arrived in this world on September the 10th, 1859.
I'd like to ask you a few questions about your early life, and the time you were born, and your schooling, and you go ahead and tell what you might, and we might ask you a few more questions.
I had my birthday, my birthday, I had a nice time.
I had a nice time.
I enjoyed it.
I enjoyed it.
The nice white people was there, and the president was there, and his wife, and shook hands with me, and just, I don't know.
I just enjoyed it.
I did.
I enjoyed it with so many people there.
And I didn't think that I had the name to be recognized enough to go on there.
I didn't think I'd be recognized enough to go on there.
But I've always had that feeling of wanting to be myself.
and the way his white and colors both of them care for me.
Whenever my colors, white and colors for me to do anything and have anything to do with them, I'd always let it, let it clean, kept myself clean, and I always tried to teach
They're nice, and I was good to them.
I was good to the children.
And I just couldn't be no better son than I was.
And I didn't care when they called for me to do anything.
I was right there ready to do it, because I'm going to try to do what I could if I know.
So that's the way I carried myself.
And I'm so proud to know that I've been mechanized enough to care for me.
Oh, and in Texas, and in the United States.
I'm so proud to know that I'm cared for in the United States.
Oh!
Oh, there's no fool not coming with me down and can't help myself.
If I felt like I couldn't help, I'd always be ready.
I'd be ready.
I'd be ready to help.
Oh, God, it's true.
I feel like I could.
I'd be ready to help.
So...
I'm down there in the king, but I've got a good desire.
I've got a good mind.
Oh, to be content, to contend on trying to do what I can by the help of the Lord.
If I can't do, if I can't do, I can speak well.
I can speak well.
Oh, it's hard to help.
Oh, as I can speak with a child of health.
Oh, and my speech.
And I trust my Heavenly Father that I can be honored enough to keep my, oh, to keep my admiration up as long as the good Lord has led me, spread me.
You know, she's family.
Well, you're speaking of your celebration.
Do you remember anything about your folks are talking about the back when you were born and that age?
Fifty-one.
And back at your mother's town about from the time you were born and where you were born, Dad?
Barn.
Yes.
I don't understand.
Celia, tell him about when you were a little baby and a little girl.
Oh, when I was a baby, I couldn't have known nothing.
I couldn't have known nothing when I was a baby.
No, sir.
You remember your mother talking about it, don't you?
Yes, sir.
Mom?
Mom.
Do you remember when you were a baby girl and you used to ride oxen and things?
Yeah.
Well, my grandfather had some big old oxen.
He had one with a big white horn.
Oh, it looked like a house.
Well, I hung there, and I used to sit up there and tune them horns.
And then his name was Coley.
His name was Coley, and the other one was named Lett.
Oh, and Grandpa didn't just drive him seriously.
where he put up children in the old ox wagon and cast them just as big as he was in a cage.
And I'd get up there in old Coley's, paint in old Coley's home and sit up there.
Sit up there and just be sitting in the house.
But the funny story, my grandfather went to town.
No one wants to get so nervous and have to go cross the river.
It's in the summertime in June, and
The old oxen got hot.
They got hot.
When they know this thing, Grandpa know this thing, the old oxen run off and run off into the river.
River said, we're dead.
We're dead.
We're away.
And I stayed up there.
And O'Cord, O'Cord his own home, picked up in O'Cord his home.
And he's waved through the water.
And the second I came down, I stayed in there, too.
I headed to his home.
I headed to his home, but I didn't pull off in the river.
I'm telling you, I headed, too.
Yes, I did.
Oh!
Oh, my grandpa was just hoping I'd get my dad to live.
And he was, and the old corner of the electric was coming through.
They come out too, yes, they did.
Celia, tell him about when you were born in Miss Clay's bed.
I did.
I was born behind this white woman.
I said, well, she was no poor woman.
No, she wasn't.
Her husband was living there.
Oh, she was no poor woman.
She brought my mother here from South Oakland up in this country.
She brought my mother here in Texas when she was young.
When my mother was young, she wasn't grown.
She brought her here.
She didn't get grown.
With her children.
Well, my father,
with my high-handsome, so-called man's name, Mr. Lawson.
Mr. Robinson was a white man, and Papa was a boy, and he did, Mr. Clay both got hired to be the yard boy for Mama.
She was like, Mr. Clay, you know,
After that, after that, after you tell the world, I was, they said, so my Papa and Mama got together.
So now I don't know how they got together.
But anyhow, my Papa and Mama,
But Mrs. Cray had my father there.
Yeah, boy, he stayed there till he was a grown young man, too, with Mrs. Cray.
Right in her yard, far out.
Her yard and her horses.
You were born in Mrs. Cray's bed?
Uh-huh.
So you were born with Mrs. Cray?
I was born right behind Mrs. Cray.
On a Tuesday morning, my mother said, my mother said to me on a Tuesday morning, my eyes were on right behind Ms. Clay in her bed.
My mother always slept with Ms. Clay when she was young, when she was 14 and 19.
And Ms. Clay, after she married,
My papa, Miss Kelly wouldn't agree for my papa to take her away from there, no.
She wouldn't.
She wouldn't agree for us to try and take her away from there.
Oh!
Oh!
In them days, them days, the white people had control over them.
When they had a color of help, it wouldn't be good for you to take them away from them.
And my mother would discuss it.
She wouldn't let nobody take her away from there.
She laid her there with her children.
With her children.
She laid them there with her boys and girls.
She didn't have but one girl.
Oh, but she had five or six boys.
She had five boys.
Miss Craig did.
Mama loved this one.
And Miss Craig good.
She didn't have one good.
And she was a big one.
She wasn't big.
She wasn't a big girl.
Oh, but she stayed out.
Until she got to be a young missus.
Oh, with mama and her brother.
She'd grown up to be in there by the dorm.
Before she, oh, I ever think about trying to get it out amongst the boys.
Oh, man.
You remember Abraham Mason?
Better than him?
Who?
I hear my mother talk about him and my father, but I never did know him.
I didn't even know him myself, but I heard them talking about him all the time.
What did they say about President Lincoln?
Oh, well, they gave him a good name.
They gave him a good name.
Oh, oh, and President Hall.
Oh, oh, they...
They gave him a pretty good name.
They gave him a pretty good name.
There's another one I know, but I forgot it.
Forgot his name.
Abraham Lincoln.
Abraham Lincoln.
That's it.
Oh, Abraham Lincoln, they thought Abraham was a beast.
They thought, everybody thought Abraham was the best citizen in the world.
They thought he was the dead best.
Did you do any picking geese or preventive edge and things like that in those days?
Did I have any?
I wasn't nothing but a kid.
I didn't have a sense of things like I got now.
I didn't have a sense of things.
I didn't know nothing about them.
Nothing.
I can tell them it's crazy to be a young business.
The only time I know anything about the company.
And then my papa had this, oh man.
Did you ever pick cotton out in the fields?
They can't.
Oh, good graces of life.
They can't.
I've raised them, see, and I've fed them.
Miss Craig, they have got mama.
I've raised them, see, and I've fed them.
Got away from Miss Craig.
Oh, my God.
I didn't do nothing, but where can I see you?
Where can I see you?
Oh, goodness.
Oh, my goodness.
Every year, I go out and go on the group.
I've got to be mad.
I'm going to wait for myself.
We go, my name, my name.
I go out west and pick cotton.
Pick cotton.
Well that was hard work.
Didn't you have some entertainment?
Do any dancing or anything?
Uh huh.
Did you dance?
Did you dance?
Dance.
Oh, I used to dance.
But I don't do it now.
No, I don't dance now.
I try my best to serve my master.
I'm trying my best to serve my head.
Help me, Father.
Silence.
I'm trying my best to serve God.
I don't study about no man.
Don't dance now.
You don't know, Mama.
You danced in your young days.
Oh, in my young days?
Yeah.
Oh, I went to balls when I was young.
Oh, when I was young, I went to dancing.
I didn't tell, I ain't gonna tell no one what I thought I went to dancing when I was young.
See, see, ma'am?
Ma'am?
Do you remember...
Going to town when you were young, were there any big buildings back then?
Oh, big building, Mama.
When you went to town when you were young, were the streets dirt?
Did you go to town in a wagon when you were a young girl?
I don't know.
Mama, you know what you used to tell us?
You used to go to town in the wagon.
Oh, oh, I did.
Oh, we used to go in a horse wagon.
I thought you were talking about something else.
Oh, yeah, we used to go in a wagon.
Celia, did you ever see a stagecoach?
Ever see what?
A stagecoach.
A stagecoach, where the people rode in the stagecoach and the horses pulled them.
Did you ever see one?
Yes, I did.
You call them and it's such a funny name that I don't know what you're talking about.
What did you call them?
I called them Hossie.
Hossie.
Neal and Hossie.
Neal and Hossie.
That's what my grandfather called them.
Neal and Hossie.
What did Mr. and Ms. Clay ride in when they would go somewhere?
in a cage, what you call it, a cage.
She called it a cage.
It was a crane down there.
A big old thing that looked like a...
Oh, you look like a cop.
Look like a cop.
Did you hear anything about the Indians at that day when you were young and the things that they did?
The Indians?
No, no, no, no.
You're talking about the Indian people.
Oh.
I had seen them, but I didn't know them.
I had seen them, but I didn't know nothing about them.
I never did get in and come to North Country with them.
I never did.
The Indians were pretty well gone at that time down here, I think, but not to the North.
Anything else you're thinking of me about there?
Well, we thank you anyway.
And we sure hope you have more birthdays.
And we're going to come up from the Panhandle, so we've been thinking of you.
We've been thinking of you.
God bless you.
Goodbye.
Goodbye.
I hope to meet you here.
If you don't leave, Andy...
This was, hopefully, the end of the war.
The end of a new war.
